WEBVTT

00:00.482 --> 00:06.949
Hear God's word from Genesis chapter 49, only verses one through seven this morning.

00:07.189 --> 00:07.970
That's exciting.

00:08.611 --> 00:09.332
Hear God's word.

00:10.913 --> 00:17.801
Then Jacob called his sons and said, gather yourselves together that I might tell you what shall happen to you in the days to come.

00:18.922 --> 00:20.143
Assemble and listen.

00:21.024 --> 00:24.708
O sons of Jacob, listen to Israel, your father.

00:25.689 --> 00:30.034
Ruben, you are my firstborn, my might.

00:31.170 --> 00:37.177
In the first fruits of my strength, preeminent in dignity and preeminent in power.

00:38.758 --> 00:45.165
Unstable as water, you shall not have preeminence because you went up to your father's bed and you defiled it.

00:46.006 --> 00:53.314
He went up to my couch, simian and Levi our brothers, weapons of violence are their swords.

00:54.656 --> 00:56.858
Let my soul come not into their counsel.

00:57.519 --> 01:00.242
Oh my glory, not be not joined to their company.

01:01.602 --> 01:03.123
For in their anger, they killed men.

01:04.725 --> 01:13.854
And in their wilfulness, the hamstrung oxen cursed be their anger for it is fierce, and their wrath for it is cruel.

01:15.155 --> 01:19.259
I will divide them in Jacob and scatter them in Israel.

01:20.540 --> 01:25.645
The grass withers and the flowers fade, but the word of our God will stand forever.

01:25.845 --> 01:26.606
And then you may be seated.

01:30.349 --> 01:31.250
Please pray with me.

01:34.434 --> 01:36.096
merciful God in heaven.

01:38.719 --> 01:44.766
We give you thanks for your love, for your children, your love that speaks to us.

01:46.848 --> 01:59.683
I pray that you would speak to us through your word this morning, that we encourage our hearts, that you would strengthen our faith and conviction, that you would stir our hearts to follow you with great vigor.

02:00.724 --> 02:02.706
We pray this in your holy name, amen.

02:06.082 --> 02:14.210
I remember when I was a teenager, I got to go to this summer camp in near Spokane called Pine Low.

02:14.830 --> 02:20.476
And like any good summer camp, they had ropes courses for you to climb and play in.

02:21.096 --> 02:27.723
And one of the ropes courses elements was this leap of faith, where you'd climb up top of this tower.

02:27.783 --> 02:30.305
And it was like 75 feet in the air.

02:30.986 --> 02:32.587
And you had a harness and a rope on.

02:32.607 --> 02:35.250
And then you'd jump out and catch this bar.

02:35.874 --> 02:42.542
And, you know, when you're on the ground, you're looking up at this thing like, okay, that seems pretty simple, looks pretty close, seems pretty doable.

02:43.383 --> 02:50.291
And then you climb up there, and you've got the harness on, they put the rope on, you know, looking at that bar, and all of a sudden it doesn't look so close.

02:51.032 --> 02:55.918
And you're like, you know, I've seen other people go before, I know that the rope will probably catch them.

02:57.079 --> 03:00.624
But also, I'm sure that there's not a 0% chance that I died doing this, you know?

03:00.944 --> 03:02.706
So you start to do the math ahead.

03:02.850 --> 03:06.156
I don't want to be that 0.01% that dies doing this trick.

03:06.837 --> 03:08.420
And he starts to wonder, can I trust the rope?

03:08.480 --> 03:11.005
Can I trust the person holding the rope down below?

03:11.045 --> 03:13.830
What if it doesn't catch me?

03:13.850 --> 03:14.491
What if I die?

03:14.531 --> 03:20.502
And I think the grace of God can be a little bit like that for us at times.

03:22.926 --> 03:24.469
We know grace is there.

03:25.050 --> 03:26.312
This is what we talk about, amazing grace.

03:26.332 --> 03:27.474
We sing the songs.

03:27.682 --> 03:29.685
We have the slogans, the grace-filled life.

03:29.765 --> 03:33.531
We got the grace-filled Bibles, the probably studied Bibles, called that somewhere.

03:34.012 --> 03:36.656
If not, this is a marketing opportunity for somebody in the room.

03:37.337 --> 03:39.039
You know, we have grace this, we have grace that.

03:39.099 --> 03:39.921
It's all over the place.

03:39.981 --> 03:41.723
It's like those words that we talk about, like gospel.

03:42.645 --> 03:45.509
But so many of us, we don't even know what these words mean, not really.

03:45.930 --> 03:48.173
Where do they hit the ground in our lives?

03:48.554 --> 03:54.162
And because of that, grace is one of these things that I think, whether we realize it or not,

03:55.202 --> 03:57.625
It's like this rope where we wonder, can we actually trust it?

03:58.345 --> 04:01.889
There's grace, which is this unmerited favor that God has for his people.

04:02.610 --> 04:03.290
Can I trust it?

04:04.231 --> 04:08.556
What I mean by that is this, what if I confess my sin?

04:09.757 --> 04:11.799
What if you know the dark corners of my heart?

04:12.940 --> 04:15.803
Will I still have favor from you and my life then?

04:17.245 --> 04:22.130
How does that favor work in my life with my sin, with my struggles?

04:23.170 --> 04:27.315
Well, grace catch me then if you knew what was going on in my life.

04:28.356 --> 04:31.119
And because of this, I think we tend to hide.

04:31.159 --> 04:33.202
We have these partial confessions.

04:33.462 --> 04:39.289
There's of course like the big ticket sins, the addictions, the legal stuff, the stuff that's going to get you in prison.

04:40.390 --> 04:46.898
But then there's the other stuff, the other stuff that we deal with daily, the insecurities that we have.

04:47.170 --> 04:50.574
So they just act in strange ways, relationally, that we just kind of keep ourselves.

04:50.594 --> 04:52.115
We never talk to anybody about it.

04:52.135 --> 05:00.345
Or the anger that boils up and boils out in our lives, or the discipline in life that we lack in different areas where we know where those areas are.

05:00.365 --> 05:02.587
But we never actually talk to anybody or seek help.

05:02.647 --> 05:05.570
Because what if this person knows that I'm weak in this area?

05:06.251 --> 05:07.132
Will they still have favor?

05:08.514 --> 05:10.255
There's all sorts of things we ignore in life.

05:11.637 --> 05:14.180
Because we're not sure, will this rope of grace hold us?

05:14.200 --> 05:16.242
Will I still have favor in community?

05:16.354 --> 05:20.901
Well, I still have favor with God if you actually knew the things I struggled with.

05:22.984 --> 05:24.787
So we suck it up, we stay quiet.

05:25.909 --> 05:41.172
And I think that the places that we hide from others are the places that we've actually struggled to trust that grace is real, that it actually is true, that it actually is amazing like we sing, which means I think we're living in almost like a half life of what we're called to live.

05:42.594 --> 05:44.978
In Genesis chapter 49,

05:45.634 --> 05:48.957
which is before us, which we're kind of slowing down as we get to this chapter.

05:48.977 --> 05:50.399
It's at the end of Genesis.

05:50.419 --> 05:51.700
There's only 50 chapters.

05:51.720 --> 05:52.361
We're almost there.

05:52.902 --> 05:57.566
But slowing down as Jacob calls his sons to himself to give them this final word.

05:59.488 --> 06:02.091
His sons are about to find out if grace will hold.

06:02.111 --> 06:07.036
I mean, he gathers them to himself, one final blessing, one final word.

06:08.478 --> 06:12.562
But if you think about these men, these men are not what you would call good men.

06:13.378 --> 06:16.041
They're liars, they're violent, they're immoral.

06:17.562 --> 06:19.484
The question is, what will the Father say to them?

06:21.366 --> 06:22.947
Now there's sins out in the open.

06:22.987 --> 06:26.291
What will the Father's final words be to His sons?

06:26.831 --> 06:30.495
And while this theme of grace may not be obvious as you're reading this, like, oh, is this really about grace?

06:30.535 --> 06:37.782
As you look at these narratives, there's these underpinning themes of Scripture that hold all the narrative of Scripture together.

06:37.882 --> 06:41.906
And I think at least one theme that we can look at here and learn

06:42.850 --> 06:55.162
A lot about is the nature of grace, which is so important for us as we think about our own futures, what holds our future together, what's our promise of the future, what's our blessing that the Lord gives us.

06:55.202 --> 07:00.607
And I think if we don't understand it in the context of grace, we actually don't understand the future that is before us.

07:01.288 --> 07:07.674
And so I think there's three things that we're gonna learn about the nature of grace that'll teach us to learn how to trust it in our lives.

07:08.835 --> 07:12.178
Those three things are these, that grace is an invitation from God,

07:13.218 --> 07:18.505
Grace is an invitation from God, saying that God first has to come to us with this invitation of grace.

07:19.527 --> 07:21.689
Secondly, grace tells the truth.

07:23.452 --> 07:24.714
Grace tells the truth.

07:24.774 --> 07:27.117
It actually holds up a mirror to your life.

07:27.798 --> 07:29.320
That's an uncomfortable part of grace.

07:29.680 --> 07:34.367
And finally, the grace forgives the greatest of sinners.

07:35.588 --> 07:37.551
The grace forgives the greatest of sinners.

07:37.591 --> 07:42.738
So look with me back here at the beginning that grace is an invitation from God.

07:47.778 --> 07:57.832
Literally back here at verse one and two, it says, and then Jacob called his sons and said, gather yourselves together, that I may tell you what shall happen to you in the days to come.

07:58.853 --> 08:03.340
Assemble and listen, those sons of Jacob, listen to Israel, your father.

08:04.842 --> 08:07.485
This is kind of beautiful scene at the end of Jacob's life.

08:07.526 --> 08:08.527
He knows he's dying.

08:08.567 --> 08:16.498
And so he's gathering his sons to himself, and it's this weighty moment.

08:17.442 --> 08:25.776
And this isn't like he's gathering people around to a hospital bed just to give them this sentimental moment that's like, hey, you know, it's great being your father.

08:25.816 --> 08:27.278
And it's not just niceties.

08:28.841 --> 08:30.523
In this moment, it's prophetic.

08:31.886 --> 08:39.177
And the words that he's gonna speak over as people are prophetic, meaning it's more than just a fortune cookie, like, hey, this could happen to you.

08:39.197 --> 08:41.261
It's like, no, this is your future.

08:42.303 --> 08:44.466
He's telling them what their future is gonna be.

08:44.866 --> 08:55.117
As the covenant family of God, as they continue to live and grow in this land, he's telling them how God's going to fulfill his mission in and through his sons.

08:56.719 --> 08:59.382
And you can almost feel at least a little bit of this tension.

08:59.422 --> 09:01.324
The sons know what's about to happen.

09:01.364 --> 09:02.625
They know that their father's calling them.

09:02.645 --> 09:03.946
They're going to say these things.

09:05.008 --> 09:06.970
And they've got to be thinking, what will he say about me?

09:08.431 --> 09:10.994
What will he say my future is going to be?

09:11.362 --> 09:14.105
What's the prophetic feature for my life?

09:14.125 --> 09:14.986
Is it going to be a blessing?

09:15.006 --> 09:16.428
Is it going to be a curse?

09:16.448 --> 09:17.028
But of both.

09:18.089 --> 09:21.994
And again, these guys are not exactly in the morality Hall of Fame.

09:22.014 --> 09:24.036
I don't know if there is one of those.

09:24.216 --> 09:25.798
I don't think any of us are probably in there either.

09:26.218 --> 09:28.701
But these guys certainly are not in there, right?

09:29.122 --> 09:34.848
Ruben slept with his father's servant, trying to overthrow him, not great.

09:34.908 --> 09:38.272
Simeon and Levi slaughtered a whole city.

09:38.312 --> 09:40.434
Again, not

09:40.514 --> 09:42.056
Great, don't recommend those things.

09:42.857 --> 09:50.388
And even the individual sins that aren't named in these guys, they all are guilty of selling their brother into slavery.

09:51.110 --> 09:52.612
Also, not great.

09:53.213 --> 09:54.314
It's pretty bad things to do.

09:54.354 --> 09:58.120
This family's a mess of violence and jealousy and all the things.

09:59.542 --> 10:07.794
And yet before you move on into the story, a fact that we can move past is this, that the Father calls them anyway.

10:09.506 --> 10:11.948
The father knows everything that these guys have done.

10:13.270 --> 10:14.210
Obviously, he's naming it.

10:14.250 --> 10:15.732
He knows who he's calling to himself.

10:15.752 --> 10:16.593
This isn't a surprise.

10:16.633 --> 10:20.516
And yet, God, I mean, the father, Jacob, calls them anyway.

10:21.738 --> 10:24.740
Before there's any correction, if there's any words, there's an invitation.

10:26.842 --> 10:30.786
This is grace, this unmerited favor of a father to his sons.

10:31.207 --> 10:34.510
They didn't earn this favor from Jacob.

10:35.390 --> 10:39.154
They did everything they could to actually destroy favor, right?

10:39.746 --> 10:45.515
Even if you just think of the selling the son, his favorite son thing, that'd be enough to destroy a father's favor towards you, but not him.

10:45.575 --> 10:47.378
He's still, you're still my son.

10:47.398 --> 10:48.940
Draw near to me.

10:49.641 --> 10:50.282
Come to me.

10:51.564 --> 10:56.011
And of course, this mirrors the way our heavenly father draws close to us.

10:57.573 --> 11:04.003
Teaching us, the first most important thing we learn about grace here is that grace searches us out.

11:05.566 --> 11:06.607
It searches you out.

11:06.627 --> 11:08.370
It has to come to you first.

11:08.930 --> 11:09.631
We don't go to it.

11:09.671 --> 11:11.473
We can't make ourselves clean.

11:11.493 --> 11:15.819
We can't dress up for it to look good to try to attract it to us.

11:15.939 --> 11:16.960
No, it finds us.

11:17.501 --> 11:18.202
We don't find it.

11:20.645 --> 11:30.418
I think this is a simple truth, but it's profound implications because I think oftentimes we imagine this scenario backwards.

11:31.778 --> 11:56.496
I think we think it's something, and maybe we find once we earn it, we know it's unmerited, but it's like maybe like half and half, you know, like half unmerited, half-merited, I mean, clearly you gotta be moving in the right trajectory to be able to get this grace towards you, something we find once we're cleaned up, once we prove ourselves, and then we get the promise of a future, because we want that grace to be like a good investment, you wouldn't wanna invest grace on somebody that's just gonna abuse it, right?

11:57.537 --> 12:00.722
I think this is how we think about it, and then we'll,

12:00.834 --> 12:02.456
We'll earn it kind of, you know?

12:03.477 --> 12:04.438
But this is not grace.

12:06.000 --> 12:09.264
By definition, it is impossible to earn this.

12:11.267 --> 12:11.848
Unmerited.

12:13.510 --> 12:17.335
You know, if you think about like merit badges, you know, how do you get a merit badge for archery?

12:17.415 --> 12:19.037
By being able to be good at archery.

12:19.057 --> 12:25.385
If you keep on missing the target, you're not going to earn a merit badge because it's given to you based on your capacity to do that thing.

12:26.786 --> 12:29.810
There's no merit badge for grace, for earning it.

12:30.370 --> 12:31.051
It's unmarited.

12:32.032 --> 12:34.196
You can never be good enough to have it.

12:34.236 --> 12:38.883
It has to come to you first and it comes to you precisely because you can do nothing to earn it yourself.

12:38.903 --> 12:43.870
That favor of God happens as God graciously comes to you.

12:46.073 --> 12:48.997
The only way you can get it is when the Father moves to you first.

12:52.122 --> 12:54.866
And this scene is echoed throughout all of scripture.

12:55.490 --> 12:57.413
The God is the God who first moves to us.

12:57.493 --> 13:00.619
It's even how our worship services mimic this.

13:01.521 --> 13:04.125
We're God's the one that calls us first and we respond.

13:04.345 --> 13:10.837
God's the one that created all things and creation responds by coming to life, even in the first sin.

13:10.897 --> 13:12.680
God's the one that goes first to Adam and Eve.

13:12.740 --> 13:15.866
Adam and Eve are not seeking God out through it, through where they're hiding from him, right?

13:16.707 --> 13:19.211
And you just go through Noah, how did Noah get found?

13:19.251 --> 13:20.754
God goes to him, Abraham.

13:21.154 --> 13:30.586
He's a pagan, God goes to him and draws him to himself and on and on from Moses to the prophets to finally in the incarnation, God is the one who's always moving first towards his people.

13:31.727 --> 13:32.909
Jesus himself is who?

13:32.929 --> 13:34.671
He's the good shepherd, the one who does what?

13:34.691 --> 13:36.393
Who chases after the lost sheep?

13:38.476 --> 13:40.258
He's the one who says he comes for the sick.

13:40.799 --> 13:49.490
Grace is a gift that's freely given that comes first to you and this teaches us that we need to understand that listen, no one can earn grace

13:50.658 --> 13:58.408
Grace is something that comes to you by God's sovereign hand, inviting you to Himself, and you come to Him empty-handed.

14:01.251 --> 14:06.037
I think sometimes people can wonder and they can think about this, okay, they can overthink it.

14:07.699 --> 14:13.386
Not that anyone in this room has been ever guilty of overthinking it, but we can wonder, well, how do I know?

14:13.426 --> 14:15.048
How do I know if I'm called?

14:15.469 --> 14:16.370
How do I know that God's

14:16.642 --> 14:17.944
invited me to his grace.

14:18.024 --> 14:26.095
Well, the fact that you're hearing these words this morning, I can assure you, God has invited you to experience his grace, to know it.

14:26.135 --> 14:28.238
He's offering you unmerited favor in him.

14:30.161 --> 14:32.244
Questions always, do we ignore this gift being offered?

14:33.766 --> 14:40.576
You know, it's one thing if you're in this room and maybe you don't have faith in Christ, this is this first time offer of grace that you receive.

14:41.237 --> 14:42.258
That's part of this.

14:43.458 --> 14:46.721
But part of this is just to ongoing walking with the Lord in life.

14:47.302 --> 14:49.264
You never outgrow your need for grace.

14:50.264 --> 14:53.608
You could be walking with the Lord for 50 years, growing in righteousness.

14:54.829 --> 14:58.052
And you still need just as much grace as anybody else in the world.

15:00.374 --> 15:01.595
You never earn this.

15:01.675 --> 15:02.776
It's always freely given.

15:03.057 --> 15:03.877
This is part of the life.

15:03.917 --> 15:05.419
We never outgrow a need of grace.

15:05.439 --> 15:06.600
You're never good enough on your own.

15:07.601 --> 15:10.043
We're called to walk in grace and grow in grace.

15:11.244 --> 15:12.946
Maybe the next question then is this,

15:13.794 --> 15:15.557
Okay, let's say God comes to us.

15:15.577 --> 15:16.339
He offers us grace.

15:16.359 --> 15:19.885
But what does it look like to answer that offer of grace?

15:19.905 --> 15:27.659
What does it look like to actually draw near to God and accept His invitation and have His grace pour into our lives?

15:27.779 --> 15:28.641
What does that look like?

15:29.042 --> 15:33.690
What does that favor look like?

15:33.710 --> 15:36.435
This is the second thing we find here is that grace tells the truth.

15:37.557 --> 15:38.098
Grace

15:39.266 --> 15:39.887
tells the truth.

15:39.947 --> 15:43.751
It comes to us first, we don't go to it, and when it finds us, it tells the truth.

15:43.811 --> 15:55.002
And this is probably the more uncomfortable part about grace, the part that doesn't often get talked about, but it's essential to be able to walk in grace in your life.

15:55.863 --> 16:02.871
Look at me back here at verse three, this is when Jacob's talking to Ruben, he's like Ruben, you're my first board, my might.

16:04.552 --> 16:06.194
And the first fruits of my strength,

16:06.978 --> 16:09.661
Preeminent in dignity and preeminent in power.

16:10.281 --> 16:13.524
Rubens got to be thinking, man, this is going pretty well so far.

16:14.105 --> 16:15.606
Maybe standing up a little straighter.

16:16.307 --> 16:17.929
I liked the way this is headed.

16:18.189 --> 16:21.212
I thought this was going to be rough, but oh, maybe he forgot about that.

16:21.732 --> 16:23.374
You know, the whole sleeping with his servant thing.

16:23.974 --> 16:25.175
And then verse four happens.

16:26.076 --> 16:27.898
Unstable is water.

16:28.859 --> 16:34.004
You shall not have preeminence because you went up to your father's bed and you defiled it.

16:34.725 --> 16:36.146
He went up to my couch.

16:38.626 --> 16:39.928
It's this weighty moment.

16:40.389 --> 16:44.296
It's like that took a turn and you can almost, you can hear the pain in his voice.

16:44.957 --> 16:48.403
Even this final phrase, he's like, he's saying it and then he's like, he's looking up.

16:48.463 --> 16:49.525
He's like, he did this thing.

16:49.845 --> 16:52.129
Can you believe that he did this thing?

16:53.311 --> 16:55.155
There's indignation, right?

16:55.215 --> 16:57.599
Ruben's sin is told for all to hear.

16:57.639 --> 17:01.746
We don't know if anyone else knew about this sin of Ruben's, but they know now.

17:03.234 --> 17:08.841
Spoken out loud for everyone to hear that he slept with his father's servant and was more than just a sexual sin.

17:09.081 --> 17:15.049
Most people will say that this was his attempt to actually overthrow his father's authority and to take control of the family.

17:16.731 --> 17:18.233
This is what he tried to do, insurrection.

17:20.055 --> 17:29.547
And it's being told for everybody when grace draws near, all right, that favor, that kindness of God that comes to our life, that acts unexpectedly.

17:29.567 --> 17:31.570
It does something we don't want it to do.

17:32.194 --> 17:35.360
It tells the truth about us, the full truth.

17:35.440 --> 17:41.270
It does not ignore your sin, nor does it ignore the consequences of sin.

17:41.551 --> 17:43.234
I mean, Ruben gets demoted.

17:43.274 --> 17:44.235
He has no more preeminence.

17:44.255 --> 17:44.917
What this means?

17:44.957 --> 17:50.226
It means like all three of these sons, they lose their place in the family.

17:50.406 --> 17:56.978
And we'll see next week that Judah actually gets, replaces them and is functionally the oldest brother in the family.

17:57.346 --> 18:05.595
He loses his place, and even his tribe kind of goes into obscurity, and there's no kings, there's no judges, there's no great leaders, no great legacy comes from him.

18:08.137 --> 18:11.120
Grace comes and it tells the truth about your life.

18:12.742 --> 18:13.183
Out loud.

18:14.824 --> 18:18.348
It gets, this continues on with Simeon and Levi here.

18:19.389 --> 18:24.114
We see this with our five to seven, these brothers, their weapons of violence are their swords.

18:24.610 --> 18:27.534
He says, let my soul come not into their counsel.

18:28.536 --> 18:30.478
Oh, my glory, be not joined to their company.

18:30.979 --> 18:33.382
From the anger they killed men in the wilderness.

18:33.402 --> 18:36.867
They hamstrung the ox and cursed be their anger for his fears.

18:36.887 --> 18:42.635
This is a wild thing where these guys came up and they slaughtered an entire city.

18:43.517 --> 18:48.644
These are men that are ruled by their anger, their violence, is their leading edge.

18:49.425 --> 18:51.628
It exposes their character flaws.

18:51.668 --> 18:53.010
And again,

18:53.890 --> 18:56.092
Grace is telling the truth of their lives.

18:56.513 --> 18:58.035
You are violent.

18:58.055 --> 18:59.236
You are to be displaced.

18:59.256 --> 19:00.237
You're going to be spread.

19:00.297 --> 19:04.201
There's consequences that these are people that become scattered.

19:04.221 --> 19:07.625
I mean, Simian's tribe dwindles.

19:07.645 --> 19:12.230
And by the end of the book of Numbers, his tribe dwindles in the smallest of all tribes.

19:12.250 --> 19:15.313
And eventually it gets absorbed into Judah's tribe.

19:18.096 --> 19:23.282
Levi's tribe never gets to inherit any land when they go into the Promised Land.

19:26.722 --> 19:31.788
The fascinating aspect of grace is that it draws us to gods and then names our sin.

19:32.729 --> 19:34.331
And actually names the cost of our sin.

19:35.112 --> 19:37.956
When grace comes to you, it does not first flatter you.

19:41.019 --> 19:42.201
It's not sentimental.

19:42.862 --> 19:46.987
It tells the truth, which is very uncomfortable and not actually what we want.

19:48.268 --> 19:50.111
When we think of grace, what do we want?

19:50.171 --> 19:52.574
We want that favor to come to us and say, you know what?

19:52.594 --> 19:53.214
You're awesome.

19:53.655 --> 19:56.178
Don't worry about all those mistakes you made.

19:56.386 --> 19:57.107
That's what we want.

19:58.228 --> 20:04.414
We want grace to come to us and be like, uh, you know, so you slaughtered a city.

20:04.494 --> 20:05.795
I've seen people slaughtered more.

20:06.035 --> 20:07.136
Not that big a deal, right?

20:07.537 --> 20:08.538
So you slept with my servant.

20:08.678 --> 20:10.259
Ah, there's people have done worse in the Bible.

20:10.379 --> 20:12.441
You know, not that, not that big a deal.

20:12.461 --> 20:13.102
That's what we want.

20:13.182 --> 20:21.050
We want that soft and sentimental grace that just wishes away our sin and so we can just move on already.

20:22.171 --> 20:23.092
We want cheap grace.

20:23.492 --> 20:24.072
That's what that is.

20:24.833 --> 20:25.714
It's a cheap grace.

20:26.338 --> 20:27.079
Why do we want that?

20:27.099 --> 20:28.361
Because I think we're afraid to be seen.

20:30.044 --> 20:35.873
Because deep down we wonder, can grace actually handle the full picture of what I've done in life?

20:37.615 --> 20:42.223
We know grace saves sinners, but this is like this kind of sinner, right?

20:44.246 --> 20:45.468
But this isn't real grace.

20:47.110 --> 20:49.133
This kind of grace actually will not help you.

20:50.896 --> 20:52.178
If you can't merit this,

20:52.770 --> 20:58.759
If grace is something you can't merit in life, or if this is favor, it has to be able to handle the fullness of our story.

21:00.021 --> 21:06.270
And that's the real grace we see here, the real grace that heals, that gives you a future, handles the fullness of your story.

21:07.272 --> 21:10.917
Because grace doesn't come to you despite your needyness, but because you're needy.

21:14.242 --> 21:16.405
We tend to have two different responses to this kind of thing.

21:16.425 --> 21:18.609
There's two different kinds of people that respond to this.

21:18.689 --> 21:22.194
And some of you,

21:22.530 --> 21:44.972
Struggle with only dwelling on your problems on your failures where that's your inner inner monologue and your voice is just constantly telling you that you're not good enough you have no problem accepting Your weakness and your failure And you know your failures live rent-free in your mind Others are the opposite where you tend to minimize?

21:46.033 --> 21:51.218
Your neediness you tend to minimize the sin in your life like that's not that big deal and you kind of

21:51.522 --> 21:56.367
You have a conscience that's not easily offended, and it's not always good, right?

21:58.530 --> 22:06.839
You assume that you're basically good, and I think what Grace does in this moment of confrontation of telling the truth, it actually confronts both those tendencies.

22:07.900 --> 22:13.287
Because as it holds a mirror to your life, as it shows you the truth, it shows you the truth.

22:14.027 --> 22:17.631
Not more than the truth, you're not worse than you think you are, but you're not better than you think you are.

22:17.671 --> 22:19.954
It's just the truth.

22:21.218 --> 22:27.827
And grace can actually show you this full truth precisely because it is strong enough to handle it.

22:29.690 --> 22:35.037
And it has to be able to tell you the truth and you have to be able to accept the truth about your neediness, about the sin in your life.

22:36.078 --> 22:47.694
Because for you to actually experience the sweetness and how sweet forgiveness is, you have to understand that God knows full well what he is forgiving in your life.

22:49.217 --> 22:50.258
He's not surprised.

22:50.434 --> 22:51.456
by your sin struggles.

22:54.120 --> 22:55.723
He's not like, oh, yeah, forgiven.

22:55.843 --> 22:59.268
And then all of a sudden you're like, but did you see this page of my life?

22:59.368 --> 23:00.791
And he's like, oh, well, what about that?

23:00.811 --> 23:01.552
I don't know about that one.

23:01.572 --> 23:02.373
That's not how it works.

23:02.433 --> 23:03.495
It's full.

23:04.998 --> 23:06.360
And we have to understand that.

23:06.680 --> 23:08.664
He sees it all and that he forgives it.

23:08.704 --> 23:15.154
Grace in some ways has to kill us before it can raise us to new life.

23:16.610 --> 23:19.313
And we can trust it to do this because of what grace does next.

23:19.413 --> 23:24.359
As grace comes to us, if grace finds us, it's the favor the Lord finds us first.

23:25.900 --> 23:30.706
As that grace shows us the truth of the reality of our lives, it does that.

23:31.887 --> 23:38.294
That's that you wallow in your sin and you just feel bad about yourself so that you can experience the fullness of the forgiveness it's offered in the gospel.

23:39.055 --> 23:45.042
This is the final thing we see here is that grace forgives the greatest of sinners.

23:46.146 --> 23:48.629
The grace forgives the greatest of sinners.

23:49.330 --> 23:53.055
I will say, this point is not obvious in this narrative.

23:54.116 --> 23:59.663
Especially in these first three candidates, all we see is their loss, their displacement.

24:01.705 --> 24:08.914
But first, before we get into the weeds a little bit, I want you to first, again, just consider the basic setting of this text.

24:09.956 --> 24:15.122
Despite these guys sin, they still get called sons, they still get drawn to Jacob,

24:16.994 --> 24:17.795
There's still sons.

24:19.097 --> 24:21.701
None of these men are disowned, even in their judgment here.

24:23.083 --> 24:24.125
They still have tribes.

24:24.145 --> 24:26.468
They're still part of this covenant family.

24:27.410 --> 24:33.759
This is kind of this beautiful first truth about this forgiveness is that grace doesn't kick them out of the family.

24:34.160 --> 24:36.764
There's consequences, but they're forgiven.

24:36.784 --> 24:37.425
They're still in.

24:37.485 --> 24:42.412
And I think we see this truth most fully in Levi's story.

24:42.432 --> 24:43.634
You see at the end of this,

24:44.002 --> 24:50.990
Verse seven, curse be their anger for this fierce and their wrath for this cruel divide them and Jacob and scatter them in Israel.

24:51.170 --> 24:52.611
You know, it's a story of scattering.

24:52.672 --> 24:54.934
Again, Levi's family does not inherit any land.

24:55.355 --> 24:56.195
They have no home.

24:57.497 --> 25:00.500
And then something unexpected happens to Levi's lineage.

25:02.723 --> 25:06.967
You know, the Levites become, they become the priests of the land.

25:08.509 --> 25:09.130
It's interesting.

25:09.750 --> 25:13.074
You know, priests did.

25:13.186 --> 25:16.009
God's grace to the people of God.

25:18.411 --> 25:21.994
They're the ones that offer the sacrifice that lead the people in temple worship.

25:22.034 --> 25:27.019
In other words, the Levites were like the pastors to the people.

25:29.341 --> 25:40.492
The descendants of a murderer, the descendants of a murderer became the pastors to God's people, to a whole nation.

25:41.893 --> 25:42.674
Isn't that wild?

25:43.618 --> 26:05.326
But if you think about it, who better to mediate the grace of God to the people of God than those who have felt it most deeply, than those who have stared into the mirror of their lives, that have reckoned with the reality of their sin, and have accepted this offer to grace, and now they can freely mediate that to the people.

26:07.189 --> 26:08.551
It's a beautiful reality.

26:09.372 --> 26:11.154
God doesn't merely forgive.

26:11.394 --> 26:12.956
His people, He repurposes them.

26:13.036 --> 26:18.562
He takes our wounds and gives them a vocation of grace in our lives and in this world.

26:20.184 --> 26:25.010
The Levites are not priests clearly because they're better, because they have this some great lineage.

26:26.972 --> 26:34.380
They're priests precisely because of the opposite, of their neediness, that they are people who have tasted deeply from the well of grace.

26:35.862 --> 26:39.506
And now that from that well that they've drunk, they're dispensing it to God's people.

26:40.162 --> 26:42.985
And this is not just a theme here, this is a theme throughout all of scripture.

26:43.005 --> 26:46.128
You know, three of the most prolific writers of the Bible were all murderers.

26:47.809 --> 26:51.553
You have Moses who murdered in Egyptian, right?

26:51.913 --> 26:54.515
That kind of set him on his trajectory out of Egypt.

26:55.336 --> 27:00.221
You have David who, trying to cover up his sin, murder demand.

27:01.602 --> 27:06.907
And the New Testament, you have Paul, once we saw, he oversaw the murder of Stephen.

27:08.849 --> 27:09.970
This is a theme of,

27:10.210 --> 27:10.871
Scripture.

27:12.853 --> 27:20.743
That God takes the wounds of our lives and applies His grace and balm and work in those places.

27:20.783 --> 27:25.188
This is true of you too, that God turns your wounds into places of ministry.

27:26.990 --> 27:31.796
And maybe at least a final question to this is, well, how does God actually do this?

27:32.637 --> 27:39.986
Like, how does this work where God can actually, both on one hand, be like this judge who's like telling us the truth

27:40.898 --> 27:46.866
And on the other hand, in the midst of Tonus, the truth about the depth of our sins, forgive us.

27:48.328 --> 27:50.130
How do these things work hand in hand?

27:50.871 --> 28:06.052
Especially when we see here the curse, again, the curse be their anger, which makes us think of Genesis chapter three, when we find out it's not just these guys that are cursed, but there's this curse that's over all creation, Christian and relationships with each other, with the land, with God himself.

28:06.633 --> 28:10.738
How does God work in the midst of this cursed world?

28:12.706 --> 28:25.460
This points us forward to then the fullness of time when another son of Jacob comes through the line of Judah, where instead of receiving blessings, the curses of a nation fall on him.

28:26.962 --> 28:40.978
Christ redeemed us from a curse by becoming a curse, which is what we read earlier in this passage that Christ in Galatians three in our in our liturgy this morning, that Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us.

28:41.410 --> 28:43.352
Cursed is everyone who hangs on a tree.

28:46.195 --> 28:48.057
This is what we see here.

28:48.097 --> 28:54.044
The Christ redeems us from this curse that we inherit by becoming the curse for us.

28:54.865 --> 29:02.513
And not only does he take the curse of our sin on himself, but he actually gives us righteousness.

29:02.553 --> 29:06.397
When his grace comes for us, when his favor comes to us, his goodness comes to us.

29:07.158 --> 29:08.620
He makes us sons and daughters.

29:08.680 --> 29:10.642
He gives us a new future.

29:10.914 --> 29:11.795
and inheritance.

29:12.817 --> 29:16.783
It's not gained by our works, but it's a gift from being found in Christ.

29:18.024 --> 29:22.651
Now when he looks at you, the favor of the Lord looks at you and he sees son.

29:23.973 --> 29:24.634
He sees daughter.

29:26.577 --> 29:33.407
He says, yes, you carry wounds and scars like Christ's body did in the resurrection.

29:34.889 --> 29:40.818
But even those become testimony of God's grace that those scars and those wounds don't define you, his grace does.

29:41.634 --> 29:43.416
His answer to your identity does.

29:43.457 --> 30:01.842
That says, listen, if God can forgive these guys, if God can forgive me, knowing the fullness of my sin, even the sins I have not yet committed, and he can raise me to new life by his grace, by his favor, and he can do this for you too.

30:03.745 --> 30:04.686
This transforms us.

30:06.669 --> 30:07.590
There's two ways this does.

30:07.630 --> 30:10.514
I think the first is it teaches us to be a people who do not hide.

30:12.130 --> 30:15.355
It teaches us to be a people who trust grace to hold us.

30:17.098 --> 30:23.427
That when grace comes to you, you can recognize it comes to you when you actually have to reckon with your sin.

30:23.488 --> 30:24.990
That is God's grace coming to you.

30:25.671 --> 30:31.179
It's actually His wrath that lets you go into sin and be unconfronted by it.

30:31.820 --> 30:35.506
The Lord disciplines the ones He loves.

30:35.714 --> 30:38.336
When by His grace it comes to you, it often comes to you.

30:38.417 --> 30:43.121
You can recognize it by showing you a mirror to your life, showing you your mistakes and your sin.

30:43.161 --> 30:46.905
And what grace says is you don't have to run from those moments.

30:49.307 --> 30:52.390
You don't have to overly dwell on them, but you don't have to run from.

30:52.410 --> 30:54.432
The verdict is in by grace you are forgiven.

30:54.772 --> 30:59.397
And because of that you can confess freely and you can trust that grace will handle your sin.

31:00.798 --> 31:05.202
The second final thing as it does is I think it teaches us to be serious about our

31:05.570 --> 31:07.412
our pursuit of holiness.

31:09.855 --> 31:14.781
I mean, because of the cost of grace is great, we ought not treat it lightly.

31:16.203 --> 31:22.751
Paul had to deal with this, you know, and people are saying, no, maybe because God's grace and mercy and forgiveness is so great, then I can just sin and do whatever I want.

31:22.811 --> 31:24.834
And he's like, no, by no means, right?

31:26.536 --> 31:35.026
It's precisely because of the grace that we're called to live up into our, live up to our name as sons and daughters of the living God, not to earn anything,

31:35.234 --> 31:41.062
But because we've already earned everything we have in Christ, we follow Him, and we grow in Him.

31:42.504 --> 31:45.508
So we learn about grace, and it's the thing that calls you to itself.

31:45.548 --> 32:05.074
It has to first come to you, and if you are hearing these words this morning, I can assure you it has come to you, and it's gonna tell you the truth, it's gonna be painful, it's gonna be a death, but it's a death that's necessary to lead you into the resurrection life with Christ, giving you a future with Him, come, receive it, taste of it, bring your sin into the light,

32:05.922 --> 32:09.827
Experience the grace of God, and as you do, extend that grace to others.

32:10.769 --> 32:12.651
Pray with me.

32:12.671 --> 32:20.001
Merciful God in heaven, we give you thanks for the truth of your grace.

32:21.844 --> 32:24.868
Father, we're a people who love to earn everything that we have.

32:27.351 --> 32:30.275
I pray that you would help us to lay our deadly doing down.

32:32.077 --> 32:35.442
If you'd help us to trust

32:35.682 --> 32:38.105
that what you have accomplished on our behalf is enough.

32:39.767 --> 32:47.196
And we walk in the fullness of this grace, and may you continue to transform our community to be a community of grace.

32:49.419 --> 32:53.924
Beyond just slogans, may it be deep and real in our lives.

32:55.747 --> 32:58.230
We pray this and trust your spirit to do this work in us.

33:00.112 --> 33:01.874
So the name of Christ, we pray, amen.

